<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n14078b"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n14" href="#n14078b">N14 (VI.B.7)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n14all.htm#n14078b"> 78(b)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> stinking / goat</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">Reason was for Luther a &ldquo;stinking goat,&rdquo; a &ldquo;deaf fool,&rdquo; whenever she took upon herself to seek contact with the supersensible. It was also on this ground that he declined to have anything to do with the Scholastics, who&mdash;more especially in the person of Thomas Aquinas&mdash; were ever appealing to reason. Aristotle, to whom, by the way, he owed his logic, <font color="green">[43]</font> he curtly dismisses as a &ldquo;hypocrite,&rdquo; a &ldquo;sycophant,&rdquo; <mark>a &ldquo;stinking goat&rdquo;</mark>! <small> Ernst Boldt, <a name="BFLS" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#BFLS"><cite title="source">From Luther to Steiner</cite></a>, (1921) 43-4</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: See also <a name="n14070g" href="n14all.htm#n14070g">N14 (VI.B.7):070(g)</a> and <a name="sa0251e" href="saall.htm#sa0251e">SA (VI.A):0251(e)</a>. </mm> </dd></dl>
